  {
    "id": "hudson_valley_franklin_d_roosevelt_presidential_library_and_museum",
    "name": "Franklin D. Roosevelt Presidential Library and Museum",
    "lat": 41.7686956,
    "lon": -73.9340591,
    "imageURL": null,
    "description": "The first presidential library in the United States — and still one of the finest — the FDR Library sits on the grounds of Springwood, the Roosevelt family estate, and tells the story of the most consequential American presidency of the 20th century with depth and care. The main museum was completely renovated in 2013 and uses a compelling mix of original artefacts, film, and interactive displays to cover the New Deal, World War II, and the remarkable partnership between Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt. FDR himself helped design the building and is buried with Eleanor in the rose garden on the grounds. The house tour (Springwood), the library, and Eleanor's cottage at Val-Kill (see below) form a natural full-day circuit that is genuinely one of the best Presidential historic site experiences in the country — more intimate and layered than most. Book tickets in advance for peak season.",
    "info": null,
    "url": null,
    "categories": [
      "historic",
      "landmark"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "hudson_valley_eleanor_roosevelt_center_val_kill",
    "name": "Eleanor Roosevelt Center-Val-Kill",
    "lat": 41.7631389,
    "lon": -73.8990976,
    "imageURL": null,
    "description": "Only two miles from Springwood and too often treated as an afterthought, Val-Kill was Eleanor Roosevelt's personal retreat and, after FDR's death, her permanent home for the last seventeen years of her life. It tells a story quite different from the Presidential Library — not of power and wartime leadership, but of Eleanor's extraordinary independent life as a diplomat, activist, and writer after her husband's death. The setting, reached by a wooded path, is modest and deeply personal: two small stone cottages, a swimming pool, furniture she chose herself. Eleanor received presidents, civil rights leaders, and foreign dignitaries here. The rangers are unusually knowledgeable, and the contrast with the grand Vanderbilt Mansion nearby is precisely the point. One of the most moving sites in the Hudson Valley",
    "info": null,
    "url": null,
