  {
    "id": "hudson_valley_saint_paul_s_church_national_historic_site",
    "name": "Saint Paul's Church National Historic Site",
    "lat": 40.893383,
    "lon": -73.82577,
    "imageURL": null,
    "description": "One of the most historically significant and least-visited National Park Service sites in the New York area. Construction was begun in 1763 and the church served throughout the Revolutionary War as a hospital, supply depot, and barracks for both the British and American armies. The church's bell tower contains a bell cast in 1758 at the same Whitechapel Bell Foundry in London as the Liberty Bell; local legend holds that George Washington ordered parishioners to bury the bell to prevent the British from melting it for ammunition. The adjacent cemetery contains legible stones from 1704, and the church interior looks much as it did in the 18th century, with its high box pews intact. The site was also the scene of the landmark Election of 1733, which raised unprecedented issues of freedom of religion and the press — a precursor to the First Amendment. The rangers are excellent, and Saturday afternoon programmes add considerable depth. The surrounding neighbourhood is not distinguished, and visiting requires a car, but the site itself is wonderful",
    "info": null,
